comment: Jack Crosby Oatts was born in Dolliver, Iowa and earned degrees from Coe College and Drake University. While serving in the Navy during WWII he attended the Navy School of Music and was a member of the Armed Forces Broadcast Band in England. He started his professional music career arranging music for Lawrence Welk. He formed the Jack Oatts Orchestra and worked out of the Des Moines area. Jack was passionate about music education and taught music at area high schools Earlham and Jefferson. He has been recognized as the “Father of Jazz Education” in the state of Iowa. His son, Dick Oatts is a famous jazz saxophonist who played with Flim & the BB’s among others

comment: John Anthony “Whoopee John” Wilfahrt was born in New Ulm, Minnesota. His polka band was a very popular attraction in the upper Midwest. Whoopee John was the second act to be signed by newly formed label Decca (Bing Crosby was the first). “Whoopee” would play Danceland often.

comment: Verne was a bandleader, bassist and concert promoter. His orchestra was based out of Denver and played throughout the Midwest. Verne Byers is also remembered as the man who, as executive producer and promoter, brought the Beatles to the Red Rocks Amphitheatre on August 26, 1964.

artist: Pee Wee King & His Golden West Cowboys / Howdy Roberts & WMT Rangers
comment: Country music songwriter and recording artist Pee Wee King was born Julius Frank Anthony Kuczynski in Milwaukee to a Polish family and lived in Abrams, Wisconsin as a youth. His father was the leader of a polka band and Pee Wee was immersed in polka and waltz music. After a stint with Gene Autry he got signed to RCA Victor and enjoyed an impressive string of hit records. By the time of this Danceland appearance Pee Wee had hits like – “Silver And Gold”, “Bimbo” and “Slow Poke”, but he is best known for co-writing the all-time classic “Tennessee Waltz”. His version was popular, but when Patti Page recorded the song it became a #1 pop hit and one of the most famous country songs in pop chart history

Eddie Sauter (mellophone, trumpet, drums) and Bill Finegan (piano) were experienced big band arrangers (Eddie with Benny Goodman; Bill with Glenn Miller). In 1952 they joined creative forces and began recording music together. The Sauter-Finegan Orchestra was known for their inventive arrangements and using a wide variety of unusual instruments. Billboard magazine described the group as “a creative band, which combines dance music as well as mood interpretations”. They were signed to RCA Victor and released a series of well-received and interesting albums. Their first big chart success was their composition “Doodletown Fifers”. They also orchestrated a Top 20 hit with the “The Moon Is Blue” from the Otto Preminger film of the same name

artist: Bill Haley & His Comets / Eddie Allen Orchestra
comment: This was the night live rock ‘n’ roll music came to Danceland. Bill “The Father Of Rock ‘n’ Roll” Haley had several hits by this time - “Shake Rattle And Roll”, “Dim, Dim The Lights (I Want Some Atmosphere)”, “Birth Of The Boogie” and Mambo Rock”.  But the Comets career really flew into another stratosphere when “(We’re Gonna Rock) Around The Clock”, was featured in the movie “Blackboard Jungle”. The movie was a hit and created a big demand for the record and the group. “(We’re Gonna Rock) Around The Clock” shot to # 1 and stayed there for five weeks earning the guys a gold record.

Sheriff Tom Owen’s Cowboys celebrate their 20 years on WMT with a get-together at Danceland. Joining them for the festivities is fellow WMT (workmate/co-worker/personality) Marshall J (real name Jay Alexander). Marshall J had a popular afternoon children’s TV show where he aired cartoons and western serials, and would spin colorful stories from his “tack room” at the WMT-TV studio

Boyd Bennett & the Rockets started making some noise in the Indiana, Kentucky, Ohio area. They came to the attention of King Records in Cincinnati. After several country flavored releases didn’t succeed, Boyd decided to try recording some of that new rock ‘n’ roll. With that in mind, Boyd wrote and recorded “Seventeen”. King released the record in June and Boyd & the Rockets toured all over the country (including this date at Danceland) to promote it. It worked. “Seventeen” became a big hit peaking at # 5 on the national charts. At the time of this appearance he had just released “My Boy – Flat Top”, which made it into the Top 40 by a hair. It is believed the Rockets lineup at Danceland was Jim “Big Moe” Muzey (vocals / trumpet), Mickey “M.D.” Allen (guitar), Roy Ayres (guitar), Bobby Jones (sax), Kenny Cobb (bass) with Boyd on drums and vocals.

Singer/songwriter fiddle player Bob Wills is known as “The King Of Western Swing”. His blending of hillbilly and big band music created quite a sensation back in the day. Bob had a string of #1 hits – “Smoke On The Water”, “Stars And Stripes On Iwo Jima”, “White Cross On Okinawa”, “New Spanish Two Step” and “Sugar Moon”. As great as those songs were, they would all pale in comparison to his classic “San Antonio Rose”.  His signature song was first recorded in 1941 as an instrumental and released again in 1944 with vocals as “New San Antonio Rose”. In the late ‘40s/early ‘50s Bob’s popularity was at its peak and his band was one of the top drawing attractions in the land. By the time of this Danceland date Bob’s glory days were in the rear-view mirror. Bob Wills was inducted into the Country Music Hall of Fame in 1968 Bob Wills was inducted into the Rock & Roll Hall of Fame in 1999 as an early influence.
